A nested f`` literal inside another f`` literal's @{ } hole, in BOTH an attr
hole and a body hole, deliberately mis-indented. The formatter reflows the
surrounding markup/Go indentation to canonical (tabs, one level per nesting)
and trims the stray spaces immediately inside the OUTER hole's own `@{ }`
boundary (the space right after `@{` and right before the matching `}`) — but
a hole whose value is itself a nested literal is not a plain Go expression the
hole-expression printer knows how to reformat, so it degrades to verbatim: the
nested literal's own text, INCLUDING its own inner `@{  who  }` hole's stray
spacing, round-trips byte-for-byte unchanged. This is the documented
"degrade-to-verbatim" behavior, not corruption — the inner hole's odd spacing
is preserved exactly, never mangled.

-- input.gsx --
package p

component Row(who string) {
        <div title={f`a @{ f`b @{ who } ` } c`}>
              {f`x @{ f`y @{  who  }` } z`}
        </div>
}
-- fmt.golden --
package p

component Row(who string) {
	<div title={f`a @{f`b @{ who } `} c`}>
		{f`x @{f`y @{  who  }`} z`}
	</div>
}
